Component has No problem and looks just as good as HDMI at 1080P.  The #1
reason for HDMI is because it's Digital, and because it's Digital you can
COPY PROTECT it with Digital Rights Management(DRM).  The #2 Reason is
Simplicity of setup, but it also has it's own problems besides the failed
connection problems because of the DRM, but because it's a tiny plug with No
type of connection to hold it securely in place like the DVI or VGA cables
for example.  This can cause picture quality problems, and you have to make
sure the cable is Secured in such a way it's not under a load.  It's just a
Bad Design.   HDMI is not the answer.  There are a couple Open formats
coming that are a lot better and I hope in the end they just replace HDMI
all together.   VGA is also a format that works quite well and with even
higher Resolutions on PC Monitors then HDMI does on HDTV's!  HDMI is just
the last thing needed to close the Analog Hole.  You can't really copy
protect a Analog Signal.   Oh sure there was Microvision for VCR's, but a
little cheap Box connected to the Video out and problem solved.  Copy away.

Unless you really need HDMI because your 1080P HDTV for some reason doesn't
have a VGA Port, though MOST DO, then a new 360 may be your only choice in
the matter, otherwise your fine with what you have, and go and just get the
larger 120 Gig HDD is you need more space, which I have for a long time now.
Quite frankly, even if you connect your 360 to your 1080P HDTV using
component, your 1080P HDTV will STILL convert it on it's own to 1080P for
display anyway, so wither the 360 does it or your HDTV does it, it's pretty
much the SAME THING.

